05604nam a22008535i 9780823290871DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20222011nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232908717 a10.1515/97808232908712doi  a(DE-B1597)565903  a(OCoLC)1306538581  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aHIS0430002bisacsh1 aPugliese, Stanislao G., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAnswering Auschwitz :bPrimo Levi's Science and Humanism after the Fall /cStanislao G. Pugliese. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2022] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (332 p.) :b9 Illustrations, black and white  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMore than twenty years ago, the Italian chemist, writer and Holocaust survivor Primo Levi fell to his death from the stairwell of his apartment building in Turin. Within hours, a debate exploded as to whether his death was an accident or a suicide and, if the latter, how this might force us to reinterpret his legacy as a writer and “survivor.” Many weighed in with thoughtful and sometimes provocative commentary, but the debate over his death has sometimes overshadowed the larger significance of his place as a thinker “after Auschwitz.” This volume contains essays that deal directly with Levi and his work; others tangentially use Levi’s writings or ideas to explore larger issues in Holocaust studies, philosophy, theology, and the problem of representation. They are included here in the spirit that Levi described himself: proud of being “impure” and a “centaur,” cognizant that asymmetry is the fundamental structure of organic life. “I became a Jew in Auschwitz,” Levi once wrote, comparing the concentration camp to a “university” of life. Yet he could also paradoxically admit, in an interview late in life, “There is Auschwitz, and so there cannot be God.” Rather than seek to untangle these contradictions, Levi embraced them. This volume seeks to embrace them as well.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 7aHISTORY / Holocaust.2bisacsh1 aAhr, Johan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaird, Marie L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBowman, Terri, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDruker, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarrell, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiuliani, Massimo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldstein, Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarrowitz, Nancy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlein, Ilona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcClellan, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMellone, James Tasato, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMisurella, Fred, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPatruno, Nicholas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPugliese, Stanislao G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPytell, Timothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScheiber, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSimon, Amy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSodi, Risa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThomson, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVandewaetere, Sara, econtributor.